\[Bishop Fitz-James] ... tried to excite the Court, with the King at
the head, against Colet, having now got hold of another weapon against
him. This was that he had openly declared in a sermon that “an unjust
peace was to be preferred to the justest war,” a war being at that very
time in preparation against the French.

The noble young King gave a conspicuous token of his kingly disposition;
for he privately encouraged Colet to go on without restraint, and improve
by his teaching the corrupt morals of the age, and not to withdraw his
light from those dark times.
